caption: I find this place very unique. Yeah its a bit small and the selection cannot compete with a fish market in flushing, but the fish they sell there is fresh. The staff is very informative, they will let you know where the fish is from, whether it was previously frozen or was it just caught. May seem pricy to some, but the words "cheap" and "quality" don't really go together. I highly recommend.

The people who work here are so personable and helpful...even with a line around the block on Christmas Eve. I just always ask me what fresh catches they are excited about that day and they have never steered me wrong.
Love this spot as a fish market and as a brunch & happy hour go-to in the pre-covid.  They’re planning to open for sidewalk dining on May 15th and I could not be more excited.

One of my favorite spot in NYC! Very high quality of food, good prices:) Would highly recommend if you are in the area!

Convenient location, nice and friendly staff. However, note that while they sell fresh oysters, they do not shuck them for you - so be prepared to spend an extra $15 to buy your own oyster knife from the store. I offered to tip because I was running low on time, but they simply don’t offer shucking. For those interested, Ocean Fish Market in Astoria (on 30th Ave) sells oysters, shucks them for free, and gives you some complimentary lemons - for around $18 per dozen oysters. Highly recommend that Greenpoint Fish & Lobster Co. offer this service.

My partner and I came by on a Friday at 5pm to beat the line-up that several reviewers mentioned. We were quickly seated and served drinks. From their happy hour menu, we ordered six of two types of oysters and six of one of their clams. All tasted fantastic. We could see them being shucked behind the bar.  My partner and I ordered the lobster roll and the mussel special. The lobster tasted fresh and the bread was crunchy and delicious. The mussels were cooked in a wine sauce and tasted fantastic.  We left at around 6pm and the restaurant was starting to get busy with all the tables full.  I highly recommend this restaurant. Definitely on my list to return to!

Very very very amazing food excellent Cooks you can tell right away, great fish sandwiches excellent lobster rolls, amazing oysters the person at the oyster bar new exactly all about the oysters I recommend this place to everybody who loves fish you need to go there excellent service and the people are very very nice there is so much more I want to say, the place might be small but it is absolutely worth the wait, oh yes the wine and the beer was very good I'm not just saying that, for service and the food like that I don't mind giving a very very nice tip and I did.

My favorite seafood place! I used to stick to another place in downtown also but after trying this restaurant in DC, I just had to find out if they have one also in NYC and I'm so glad they do! Nice and kind staffs also.

Amazing selection of oysters and best lobster roll I've ever had! We had to wait for about 30 minutes to be seated but it was totally worth it. Especially for the happy hour combination of $1.50 on select oysters and $5 beers.

Great food and staff. Definitly a weekly stop. The specials at happy hour are a great time to check this place out.

I've been here about a dozen times. Easily my favorite restaurant in greenpoint. Just be prepared for the fresh fish market smell when you walk in. It's a small place so unfortunately it doesn't accommodate many people. I'm pretty sure all the seating are two tops and then they have bar seating.  They have really a stellar oyster selection. It's a very detailed oyster list which includes location, size, taste, and type of finish. You pay per oyster and they are expensive but well worth it. Make sure you start out with an oyster or two!  Huge fan of the way they set up their menu. They have about 8 or so apps and 10 entrees. Some of the entrees are always consistent (lobster rolls, tuna burger, etc.) The other dishes like (fish tacos, rice dish, etc.) are always the same but they change out the fish with what they get fresh. So one day the fish tacos might be sword fish the next they could be cod. They usually change it daily too. Really cool concept love that idea. I've had almost all the dishes none have disappointed. The tuna burger is my favorite.  Pro tip: Get the fish taco entree as an app. Best fish tacos. There's two so perfect to share.

Not fresh, WASTE OF MONEY. I bought 2 lbs. Of mussles and when I got home I found half of them were already opened and unusable. They provided no ice to transport the mussles home, just a mesh bag in a paper bag that tore a few blocks from the store. Total Amateur hour. Not going here again, you shouldn't either.
Just because the happy hour stuff are really limited. Otherwise it is a 5 star place.

The staff was very knowledgeable and beyond friendly the whole experience felt like we were dining with long time friends. Can not wait to go back!

There is bar seating and a few tables - not a huge place inside. Going with a party larger than 3 or 4 could get a little uncomfortable. You can also buy fresh, raw seafood up front. I've been here so much with friends who visit and there's no doubt it's a good restaurant - the cooking is great, with an eye on sustainability, and everything is very fresh. It is less fancy than it seems by the 'oyster' label - feels more like a cafe than a restaurant, in a good way.  But... I've been pleasantly AND unpleasantly surprised by some of the food, especially specials, a number of times. They are sporadically expensive for the portions, and often not what you expect when they arrive. The staff are always gushing about every meal... so before you order look at what everyone else has and make sure it's what you think it is!  It's fancy-fish-101, but just because something is $30 and something else is $15, it doesn't mean the $30 item is going be a good main course. Come here and pretend you didn't see the prices and just order what you like the look of and you'll have a way better time.  As a fishmonger it is not cheap, but what can you compare it to apart from Whole Foods? Good fresh fish is a rare thing in Greenpoint. You get what you pay for... really high quality, tasty, sustainable, fresh fish, in the middle of Greenpoint, and open late - I think it's worth it if it matters to you.  Oh yeah, the Michelada is great!

Excellent seafood, but overpriced. Small, and crowded in the evenings, this half-counter, half-sit-down railroad restaurant serves tasty dishes and oysters. My single gripe is that for what amounts to, two small tacos, 5 pieces of sashimi, 6 oysters, and a piece of pie, my dinner was close to $80, which even for the area, is a bit high. I've gotten a much better deal at the Mermaid Inn Oyster Bar in the city, with comparable food choices.

The food itself is decent but I've found it to be a bit overpriced for their serving sizes.  The Fish Sandwich and the Rice Bowl both only serve you about 4 oz. of fish and both come with ~20 dollar price tags. (3 dollar upcharge for FRIES with your sandwich)  Also disappointed in the lack of methods of fish preparation for dishes. Not allowed to choose between blackened/fried/seared and such is kind of disappointing coming from a fresh fish-market.  The oysters were very fresh but they range from 3-4 dollars PER oyster and they are very small.  (Non Happy-Hour pricing)  Drinks will run you around 7 dollars for a middle of the road beer which is fine.  There is limited seating as it doubles as a fish market as well as a restaurant. The staff are nice and friendly though and it's cool that they have a rotating menu based on the market. I'd just say that they need to reduce their pricing on their entrees by about 4 dollars an item and they would be a lot more popular.

Es scheint, dass es die New Yorker lieben, aber ich mag verkohlten Fisch überhaupt nicht. Für mich ein absolutes No-go. Die restlichen Zutaten zum Taco waren ebenfalls nicht abgestimmt. Die Lobster Roll war gut, aber nicht wirklich etwas Besonderes.

Hands down, the freshest seafood you can get in the neighborhood. Whether you're dining there or buying fish to take out, the seafood is always changing seasonally and they offer an interesting variety sometimes. Like Char, Sea Robin, Porgies.... The staff is pretty friendly and knowledgeable too.

This fish market/restaurant offers lots of options on the menu. However, don't leave this place without ordering the fish and chips. The best anywhere. Just not, seating is small party or singles only.

Excellent selection of high-quality fish, shrimp, oysters and other creatures of the sea. The fish is always really fresh, and they manicure and prepare the fish so you can dive into cooking easier without having to de-scale, de-bone, de-skin. The sit-down restaurant part is also delicious. They prepare fish in 6-7 different methods (crudo, taco, bowl, etc), with each method assigned a different type of fish. Pairings change often. On the pricey side, but well worth it. Beats Whole Foods and Fresh Direct fish options.

Excellent food, not crazy expensive, served by people who will help you cook and eat better seafood and who care about responsible sourcing.

This place was awesome. There was a wait but it was worth it,  the smoked mussels are so delicious and juicy as well as the toasted sourdough bread that it is served with is delicious. The smoked bluefish pate is also a dish worth trying out, it is like a tuna mix that comes with their toasted bread and it was also very good. The lobster roll with the fries were awesome, I think I loved the fries more than roll but only because their fries genuinely taste different from others I have had but the lobster roll definitely should be ordered because it will not disappoint you. The service was great, the server made it a point to get to the table as soon as possible, poured our water, bussed as we ate and the plates kept coming, I will definitely go here again.

Stayed in Brooklyn for the evening a couple months ago and had a craving for seafood so my girlfriend and I stumbled into this place. Some of the best oysters we've ever had. I'll definitely be back next time I'm through. Thanks guys!
I've never eaten here, but I've purchased very tasty salmon from their retail section. The staff was very helpful in selecting our fish and even de-boned it while we waited!

I ordered the lobster roll. It includes buttered toast, fries, cole slaw, pickle, and lobster bits with chopped celery in it. I would nix the celery next time. It was very tasty, but definitely expensive. Menu doesnt specify the price. They charge based on market price which came out to $25 in my case. Considering Luke's Lobster is only $16 and taste very similiar, I prob would just stick with Luke's.

The best seafood I've had in all of NYC and Brooklyn!!  The lobster roll was amazing and so was my 2 pound steamed lobster.  The oysters were also delicious and the service was great.  Thanks, Greenpoint Fish and Lobster!  We'll be back!

Small nook selling fresh catch — I was too early for their lobster roll, so got the fish & chips instead, the fish was white sea bass and really meaty. Chowder cup was tasty and full of fresh chunks of fish. Would love to come back again for the lobster roll.

Overrated. Poor service. Everything takes forever to get served. They say Market Price fir a Lobster Roll, which means they will charge you $28 when you pay. Twice the price as anywhere else in the city. And the roll is really bland, with 10 soggy fries to go with it. It's a place trying to be hip but charge you trust fund prices. Avoid it and you'll be glad you saved your money rather than spending it on bland food that takes 8 people a half hour to get to you.

A rare gem of quality seafood place in Greenpoint. Fishmonger in the front, oyster shucker in the middle and a full seafood kitchen in the back. Great, fresh food all over.
